AU  - Beamish, Paul W
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/05/01
TI  - Split management control and international joint venture performance
JO  - Journal of International Business Studies
SP  - 201
EP  - 215
VL  - 35
IS  - 3
AB  - A framework is presented to characterize four different ways in which management control is partitioned between a multinational enterprise (MNE) and local partners within international joint ventures (JVs): split control management, shared management, MNE-partner-dominant management, and local-partner-dominant management. The framework was tested using a sample of international JVs in Korea. We found that JVs following the split control management performed better than any other approach. No performance differences were found among the remaining three types of management control. This suggests that MNEs and local partners should split control: that is, choose the activities to control so that those chosen activities can be matched with their respective firm-specific advantages.
